Facsimile Signatures 185. 8 Amendments; Term 185. 9 Further Assurances 185. 10 WAIVER OF RIGHT TO PARTITION 18AMENDED AND RESTATED LARGE GENERATOR INTERCONNECTION AGREEMENTCO-TENANCY AGREEMENTThis LARGE GENERATOR INTERCONNECTION AGREEMENT CO-TENANCY AGREEMENT (this “Agreement”) is made and entered into as of May 24, 2016, by and among Elevation Solar C LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (“Elevation Solar C”), Western Antelope Blue Sky Ranch B LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (“WABSRB”), Antelope Big Sky Ranch LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (“ABSR”), Summer Solar LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (“Summer Solar”), Antelope DSR 1, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (“DSR 1”), Antelope DSR 2, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (“DSR 2”), Antelope DSR 3, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (“DSR 3”), Solverde 1, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (“Solverde 1”), Bayshore Solar A, LLC (“Bayshore Solar A”), Bayshore Solar B, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (“Bayshore Solar B”), and Bayshore Solar C, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (“Bayshore Solar C”) (each a “Co-Tenant” and, collectively, the “Co-Tenants”), and Sustainable Power Services, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (the “Manager”). Each Co-Tenant and the Manager may be referred to as a “Party” and, collectively, as the “Parties”. RECITALSA. The Co-Tenants are developing and will construct, own and operate a solar photovoltaic energy project with an aggregate capacity of approximately 330 net MW (collectively, the “Big Sky Solar Project”) in Lancaster, California. B. Each Co-Tenant will construct, own and operate a separate phase (each, a “Phase”) of the Big Sky Solar Project. C. The Phases to be constructed, owned and operated by each of Elevation Solar C, WABSRB, ABSR, Summer Solar, DSR 2, DSR 1, Solverde 1, Bayshore Solar A, Bayshore Solar B, Bayshore Solar C, and DSR 3 are projected to have a net nameplate capacity of 40 MW, 20 MW, 20 MW, 20 MW, 5 MW, 50 MW, 85 MW, 20 MW, 20 MW, 20 MW, and 30 MW, respectively. D. The Co-Tenants, as tenants-in-common, have entered into the First Amended Large Generator Interconnection Agreement dated April 13, 2016 by and among the Co-Tenants, as tenants-in-common, Southern California Edison Company (“SCE”) and the California Independent System Operator Corporation (the “CAISO”) (together with all agreements, schedules, appendices, exhibits and other documents ancillary thereto (including the Meter Service Agreement and the Participating Generator Agreement), all as may be further amended or supplemented, the “LGIA”) for the purpose of securing interconnection rights for the Big Sky Solar Project and each of the Phases. E. The Parties desire to enter into this Agreement to set forth the rights and obligations of each of the Parties under the LGIA on the terms and conditions set forth herein. NOW, THEREFORE, in consideration of the foregoing and the agreements and covenants contained herein, and other good and valuable consideration, the receipt and sufficiency of which are hereby acknowledged, the Parties hereto agree as follows:AGREEMENT DEFINITIONS Certain Definitions. CO-TENANCY RIGHTS AND OBLIGATIONS[RESERVED]. Use of LGIA. The LGIA shall be held and used solely to permit the interconnection of electricity generated by or on behalf of a Phase owned by a Co-Tenant (or by such Co-Tenant’s successors or assigns) at the Antelope Substation. Each Co-Tenant shall have an undivided ownership interest as tenant-in-common in the rights and obligations of the Interconnection Customer and the LGIA equal to its Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest, and possess an undivided right to enjoy all of such interest in the Interconnection Customer under the LGIA. Maximum Capacity. No Co-Tenant shall interconnect its respective Phase to the Antelope Substation to the extent such interconnection will result in such Co-Tenant having a Phase with a Net Nameplate Capacity in excess of the Interconnection Capacity allocated to such Phase in the LGIA. To the extent that conditions exist which result in a Co-Tenant generating energy from its respective Phase in excess of its Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest of the Interconnection Capacity, then such Co-Tenant shall curtail the operation of its Phase so as not to exceed its Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest of the Interconnection Capacity. Curtailment. In the event of any curtailment of interconnection services at the direction of CAISO or Participating TO, such curtailment shall be allocated pro rata among the Co-Tenants according to each Co-Tenant’s Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest; provided, however, that the Manager shall only curtail on a non-pro rata basis if such allocation is necessary to comply with the LGIA or CAISO or Participating TO direction, and, in each case, that such non-pro rata allocation will not result in a default under the LGIA or any PPA to which a Co-Tenant is a party. LGIA Expenses. Each Co-Tenant hereby confirms its obligation to share in the periodic payment of all expenses incurred under the LGIA in accordance with its Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest. (a) Construction Costs. Each Co-Tenant hereby agrees to fund its Cost Allocation Percentage of all Construction Costs required to design, engineer and construct the Participating TO’s Interconnection Facilities. With respect to the Interconnection Customer’s Interconnection Facilities being constructed pursuant to the LGIA, each Co-Tenant shall fund its share of the Construction Costs pursuant to the terms of the EPC Agreement and the Future EPC Agreement. Upon the delivery of notice by Summer Solar, WABSRB, Elevation Solar C, or ABSR pursuant to Section 2. 8, such Co-Tenant shall promptly reimburse each other such Co-Tenant for an amount equal to the difference between (i) the amount of Construction Costs for the Participating TO’s Interconnection Facilities previously paid by such Co-Tenant, minus (ii) such Co-Tenant’s Cost Allocation Percentage (after delivery of such notice) of all Construction Costs for the Participating TO’s Interconnection Facilities previously paid by such other Co-Tenants, plus interest at the Interest Rate. Bayshore Solar A, Bayshore Solar B and DSR 3 will be exclusively responsible for all Interconnection Customer’s Interconnection Facilities and associated costs that will be described in the Future EPC Agreement, including any reallocation of the Construction Costs for the Interconnection Customer’s Interconnection Facilities associated with any change in the Net Nameplate Capacity of the Bayshore Solar A Phase, the Bayshore Solar B Phase or the DSR 3 Phase. (b) LGIA Operating Expenses. Each Co-Tenant shall be responsible for the payment of its share, if any, of the LGIA Operating Expenses according to such Co-Tenant’s Cost Allocation Percentage. Each Co-Tenant shall be responsible for the payment of its share, if any, of costs that occur under the LGIA that are not LGIA Operating Expenses according to its respective Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest. (c) Payment of LGIA Expenses. The Manager shall, as authorized agent for each Co-Tenant, administer the collection and payment of the LGIA Operating Expenses and other amounts due from the Interconnection Customer under the LGIA. Each Co-Tenant obligated to pay LGIA Operating Expenses and other amounts under the LGIA shall pay each invoice for LGIA costs promptly upon receipt of written notice thereof from the Manager, but in any event within thirty (30) days of such receipt or such earlier time as required by the LGIA. Liquidated Damages; Credits, Refunds. To the extent that the Manager receives any damages, credits or refunds pursuant to the LGIA, the Manager shall promptly remit such damages, credits or refunds to the Co-Tenants according to each Co-Tenant’s Cost Allocation Percentage (unless such damages, credits or refunds accrue to a specific Co-Tenant, in which event the Manager shall promptly remit them to such Co-Tenant). Joint and Several Liability. Each Co-Tenant shall be jointly and severally liable for (i) any payments due under the LGIA imposed on the Interconnection Customer and (ii) the performance of the obligations and duties imposed on the Interconnection Customer by the LGIA; provided, however, that each Party shall be severally, and not, jointly liable for all other obligations hereunder. Projected Capacity. To the extent that the Net Nameplate Capacity for a Phase differs from the value identified in the LGIA or Exhibit A to this Agreement, a Co-Tenant shall notify the Manager and the other Co-Tenants in writing, no later than thirty (30) days before such Co-Tenant’s Construction Commencement Date, of the Net Nameplate Capacity of its Phase, provided that each Co-Tenant’s Net Nameplate Capacity is subject to Section 2. 3 and may not exceed such Co-Tenant’s Maximum Net Nameplate Capacity. The Co-Tenancy Percentage Interests and, for Summer Solar, WABSRB, Elevation Solar C, and ABSR, the Cost Allocation Percentage, shall be adjusted to reflect such notice. Indemnity. (a) Each Co-Tenant (an “Indemnifying Co-Tenant”) shall indemnify, defend and hold harmless the other Co-Tenants (each, an “Indemnified Co-Tenant”) from and against any and all losses (including all lost revenues under applicable PPAs), damages, liabilities, claims, judgments, liens, penalties, costs and expenses, including, without limitation, reasonable attorneys’ and consultants’ fees (collectively, “Claims”), which may be imposed upon or incurred by such Indemnified Co-Tenant or asserted against such Indemnified Co-Tenant in connection with any breach by the Indemnifying Co-Tenant of this Agreement or the LGIA. (b) The Manager shall indemnify, defend, and hold harmless the Co-Tenants from any Claims which may be imposed upon or incurred by such Co-Tenants as a result of fraud, willful misconduct, or gross negligence of the Manager, or in connection with any breach by the Manager of this Agreement or the LGIA. Taxes. Each Co-Tenant shall pay all real and personal property taxes and assessments, general or special, levied against its Phase, except for any taxes or assessments that are LGIA Operating Expenses. All such taxes and assessments shall be paid before delinquency and before any fine, interest or penalty shall become due or be imposed for their non-payment; provided if a Co-Tenant in good faith contests or disputes such taxes or assessments and furnishes to the other Co-Tenants a bond or other acceptable security in an amount sufficient to discharge all such contested taxes or assessments, such Co-Tenant will not be in default under this Section 2. 10 for failing to timely pay such contested taxes or assessments. Operation and Management. (a) Each Co-Tenant shall operate and maintain its Phase Controlled Assets acting as a prudent operator and manager and otherwise (a) in accordance with the terms of the LGIA, (b) in accordance with good operating and utility industry practices, in compliance with all applicable Laws, including but not limited to the Federal Power Act, as amended (“FPA”), and all rules, regulations, and orders issued by the FERC pursuant to the FPA, (d) in compliance with the CAISO Tariff, including the rules, protocols, procedures and standards attached thereto, as the same may be amended from time to time and approved by FERC, (e) in compliance with the rules, protocols, procedures and standards of NERC, as applicable, and (t) without causing a material adverse effect on the LGIA. (b) Each Co-Tenant shall comply with its obligations under the LGIA, including with respect to its obligations to fund LGIA Operating Expenses. Each Co-Tenant shall obtain and maintain status under applicable Law as an “exempt wholesale generator” or, if, and for so long as, such Phase meets the criteria of a qualifying small power production facility, as set forth in 18 C. F. R. § 292. 204, a “qualifying facility. ”(c) Each Co-Tenant shall cooperate with and timely respond to Manager as agent for the Co-Tenants under the LGIA, and shall provide Manager such information required by Manager to comply with its obligations under the LGIA. (d) With respect to jointly held assets, the Co-Tenants may delegate to the Manager some or all of their respective obligations under this Agreement. Events of Default; Default. The following shall constitute “Events of Default”: a Party fails to perform its obligations under this Agreement or the LGIA in any material respect, and such Party fails to cure such default within (i) ten (10) days after receipt of written notice of a payment default, or (ii) twenty (20) days after receipt of written notice of any non-payment default, provided if the nature of the defaulted obligation or obligations other than a payment default is such that more than thirty (30) days are required, in the exercise of commercially reasonable diligence, for cure of such default, then such Co-Tenant shall not be in default under this Section 2. 12 if it commences to cure such default within twenty (20) days after receiving notice of the default and thereafter continuously pursues the same to completion with commercially reasonable diligence, such extended period not to exceed sixty (60) days, including the initial cure period. Remedies. Subject to the last sentence of Section 5. 8, in addition to all other remedies permitted by Law or under this Agreement (all of which shall be cumulative), following an Event of Default, each non-defaulting Party shall have the right, but not the obligation, to perform the obligations of the defaulting Party, and the defaulting Party shall reimburse the performing Parties for their expenses which they incurred in rendering the performance, plus interest at the Interest Rate. Disconnection. (a) If a Co-Tenant fails to cure any default of it under this Agreement or the LGIA within twenty five (25) days after receiving notice of such default, the Manager may disconnect the breaching Co-Tenant’s Phase from the Antelope Substation (i) after obtaining written approval to do so from the Co-Tenants then not in default, or (ii) without approval from the Co-Tenants then not in default but only to the extent necessary to prevent or cure a “Default” under the LGIA; provided if the nature of the defaulted obligation or obligations is such that more than thirty (30) days are required, in the exercise of commercially reasonable diligence, for cure of such default, then the Manager may not disconnect the defaulting Co-Tenant’s Phase if such Co-Tenant commences to cure such default within twenty five (25) days after receiving notice of the default and thereafter continuously pursues the same to completion with commercially reasonable diligence, such extended period not to exceed eighty five (85) days, including the initial cure period; provided further, that in no event shall any cure period hereunder extend beyond any applicable cure period under the LGIA. (b) To the extent caused by a Co-Tenant’s default hereunder, the Manager may also disconnect such Co-Tenant’s Phase in order to prevent damage to the other Co-Tenants’ Phases, the Interconnection Facilities or the property of the Participating TO or as otherwise needed to prevent or mitigate technical issues affecting the Phases; the Manager shall immediately notify the Co-Tenants of any such disconnection. Equitable Relief. The Parties agree that damages may be an inadequate remedy for a breach by the Manager or any other Party of its respective obligations under this Agreement, and that each Party shall be entitled to seek injunctive and other equitable relief, including specific performance, against any other Party or the Manager to prevent or eliminate such default. Dispute Resolution. (a) Submission. In the event any Party has a dispute, or asserts a claim, that arises out of or in connection with this Agreement or the LGIA, such Party (the “Disputing Party”) shall provide the other Parties with written notice of the dispute or claim (“Notice of Dispute”). Such dispute or claim shall be referred to a designated senior representative of each Party for resolution on an informal basis as promptly as practicable after receipt of the Notice of Dispute by the Parties. In the event the designated representatives are unable to resolve the claim or dispute through unassisted or assisted negotiations within thirty (30) days of the other Parties’ receipt of the Notice of Dispute, such claim or dispute may, upon mutual agreement of the Parties, be submitted to arbitration and resolved in accordance with the arbitration procedures set forth below. In the event the Parties do not agree within such thirty (30) day period to submit such claim or dispute to arbitration, each Party may exercise whatever rights and remedies it may have in equity or at law consistent with the terms of this Agreement. (b) Arbitration Procedures. Any arbitration initiated under this Agreement shall be conducted before a single neutral arbitrator appointed by the Parties. The arbitrator shall be knowledgeable in electric utility matters, including electric transmission and bulk power issues, and shall not have any current or past substantial business or financial relationships with any party to the arbitration (except prior arbitration). The arbitrator shall provide each of the Parties an opportunity to be heard and, except as otherwise provided herein, shall conduct the arbitration in accordance with the rules and procedures for arbitration of complex business disputes for Judicial Arbitration and Mediation Services, Inc. (“Arbitration Rules”) and any applicable FERC regulations; provided, however, in the event of a conflict between the Arbitration Rules and the terms of this Section 2. 16, the terms of this Section 2. 16 shall prevail. (c) Arbitration Decisions. Unless otherwise agreed by the Parties, the arbitrator shall render a decision within ninety (90) days of appointment and shall notify the Parties in writing of such decision and the reasons therefor. The arbitrator shall be authorized only to interpret and apply the provisions of this Agreement and the LGIA and shall have no power to modify or change any provision of such agreements in any manner. The decision of the arbitrator shall be final and binding upon the Parties, and judgment on the award may be entered in any court having jurisdiction. The decision of the arbitrator may be appealed solely on the grounds that the conduct of the arbitrator, or the decision itself, violated the standards set forth in the Federal Arbitration Act or the Administrative Dispute Resolution Act. The final decision of the arbitrator must also be filed with FERC if it affects jurisdictional rates, terms and conditions of service, Interconnection Facilities, or Network Upgrades. (d) Costs. Each Co-Tenant shall be responsible for its own costs incurred during the arbitration process and for such Co-Tenant’s Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest of the cost of the arbitrator chosen, if applicable. Effect of Force Majeure. If, because of an event of Force Majeure, any Party is unable to carry out its obligations under this Agreement, and if such Party promptly gives the other Parties written notice of such Force Majeure in detail, specifying the nature, extent and expected duration of such Force Majeure, the non-payment obligations and liabilities of the Party giving such notice and the corresponding obligations and liabilities of any other Party shall be temporarily suspended to the extent made necessary by and during the continuance of such Force Majeure; provided, that in no event will the suspension of a Party’s obligations and liabilities hereunder be permitted to cause a “Default” under the LGIA. Any disabling effects of such event of Force Majeure shall be eliminated as soon as and to the extent reasonably practicable by the Party claiming Force Majeure. Notice of Default. Each Co-Tenant and the Manager shall promptly provide written notice to the other Parties upon receiving notice of, or otherwise discovering, any default or potential default under this Agreement or the LGIA or receiving any other notice under the LGIA. Generator Downsizing Process. In the event that the Commercial Operation Date with respect to a Phase is reached and such Phase has a total megawatt capacity amount that is lower than the amount specified in the LGIA by an amount greater than the de minimis threshold of Appendix DD of the CAISO Tariff, the Manager shall submit (on behalf of such Interconnection Customer), or cause such Interconnection Customer to submit, a completed Generator Downsizing Request application and deposit with respect to the uncompleted capacity of such Phase to the CAISO during the last Generator Downsizing Request Window applicable to such Phase. The Co-Tenant for such Phase will be responsible for payment of all deposits and other obligations for study costs, executing agreements required by CAISO in the Generator Downsizing Process, all costs to amend the LGIA and any other costs incurred in connection with the Generator Downsizing Process. MANAGERAppointment of Manager; Manager Services. Each Co-Tenant hereby appoints the Manager to act as its agent and representative for all purposes under the LGIA, and, unless otherwise agreed by the Co-Tenants, the Manager shall have the power to exercise and shall exercise any and all of the rights of the Interconnection Customer under the LGIA and shall coordinate compliance with the LGIA by the Co-Tenants; provided that the Manager may not terminate, amend or Transfer the LGIA or waive any material rights of the Co-Tenants under the LGIA or initiate or settle any dispute resolution under the LGIA, without the prior, unanimous written consent of the Co-Tenants. In addition, each Co-Tenant specifically authorizes the Manager to negotiate and, with the Co-Tenants’ prior written consent, execute on its behalf and on behalf of the Interconnection Customer, and agrees to be bound by the terms of, (i) a CAISO meter service agreement, (ii) a CAISO participating generator agreement and (iii) a retail electricity service agreement; provided that, to the extent that the Manager acts as agent for the Co-Tenants under any such agreement, the Manager may not terminate, amend or Transfer any such agreement or waive any material rights of the Co-Tenants under any such agreement or initiate or settle any dispute resolution under any such agreement, without the prior written consent of a Majority of the Co-Tenants. Communications. The Manager shall be the single point of contact between the Co-Tenants and the CAISO and the Participating TO, and shall be responsible for all administrative obligations of the Interconnection Customer under the LGIA, including billing, issuing payments, providing notices and communicating with, and receiving instructions from, the CAISO and the Participating TO with respect to the Phases and the LGIA. The Manager shall, promptly upon receipt, provide to each Co-Tenant a copy of any notices or other material communications received by it under the LGIA. Indemnification of Manager. Each Co-Tenant shall, pro rata in accordance with its Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest, defend, indemnify and hold harmless the Manager and its employees and agents, from any claim, loss, liability or damage incurred by reason of any act performed or omitted to be performed by it in its reasonable judgment, in good faith, or in reasonable reliance on advice of the Manager’s attorneys or accountants, in connection with the LGIA or this Agreement (other than acts or omissions constituting a material breach by the Manager of this Agreement or the fraud, willful misconduct, or gross negligence of the Manager), including reasonable attorneys’ fees incurred by it in connection with the defense of any action based on any such alleged act or omission. The Manager shall specifically be indemnified by the Co-Tenants (pro rata in accordance with their Co-Tenancy Percentage Interests) and held harmless from any and all actions taken by the Manager in its reasonable judgment, in good faith, or in reasonable reliance on advice of the Manager’s attorneys or accountants, and shall be reimbursed by the Co-Tenants (pro rata in accordance with their Co-Tenancy Percentage Interests) for costs, which arise in connection with the LGIA or this Agreement (other than costs resulting from a material breach by the Manager of this Agreement or the fraud, willful misconduct, or gross negligence of the Manager). Books and Records; Reporting Requirements. (a) Maintenance or Records. The Manager shall maintain books and records in sufficient detail to verify amounts due and payable hereunder for a period of not less than three (3) years after the end of the calendar month to which they relate, and all such books and records shall be available for inspection and/or copying by each Co-Tenant or its authorized representative at the cost and expense of such Co-Tenant and at reasonable times during regular business hours, upon reasonable notice to the Manager. (b) Provision of Records. The Manager shall, from time to time or at the reasonable request of the Co-Tenants or their Financing Parties, provide reports to the Co-Tenants and their Financing Parties sufficient to keep the Co-Tenants and their Financing Parties reasonably apprised as to significant matters concerning the LGIA, the Construction Costs and the LGIA Operating Expenses. Replacement of Manager. Upon the written approval of a Majority of the Co-Tenants, the Co-Tenants may replace the Manager with any Person of their choosing; provided, however, that any Co-Tenant (acting by itself) may remove the Manager if the Manager is in material default hereunder. If a Co-Tenant (acting by itself) removes the Manager as a result of a material default hereunder, the Co-Tenants shall jointly appoint a new Manager and provide written notice to CAISO and Participating TO of the new Manager. Upon any replacement of the then-existing Manager, the then existing-Manager shall no longer be a Party hereunder and the new-Manager appointed by the Co-Tenants shall be the Manager hereunder. The new Manager shall execute a joinder to this Agreement and provide its contact information pursuant to Section 5. 1. Omitted. Discrimination. Notwithstanding any other provision herein to the contrary (other than Section 2. 4 and 2. 14), the Manager shall not discriminate in providing services or otherwise performing its obligations hereunder among the Co-Tenants. As used herein, “Discriminate” means a failure by the Manager to provide services hereunder in a manner that treats alike each of the Co-Tenants under substantially similar conditions, and for which dissimilar treatment is not otherwise justified as necessary in accordance with prudent operating and utility industry practices. Performance. The Manager shall perform its obligations under this Agreement (a) in accordance with the terms of the LGIA, (b) in accordance with good operating and utility industry practices, (c) in compliance with all applicable Laws, including but not limited to the FPA, and all rules, regulations, and orders issued by the FERC pursuant to the FPA, (d) in compliance with the CAISO Tariff including the rules, protocols, procedures and standards attached thereto, as the same may be amended from time to time and approved by FERC, (e) in compliance with the rules, protocols, procedures and standards of NERC, if applicable, and (f) without causing a material adverse effect on the LGIA. Termination of LGIA. In the event that CAISO and/or SCE seeks to terminate the LGIA and any Co-Tenant objects to such termination, the Co-Tenants and Manager shall cooperate and take such joint actions as may be reasonably necessary or advisable, in each case, to prevent such termination, including, submitting a written objection to CAISO and/or SCE and/or filing a protest or complaint with FERC. TRANSFERABILITYGeneral Restriction. Manager shall not Transfer its rights and obligations under this Agreement. No Co-Tenant may Transfer its rights and obligations under this Agreement or the LGIA; provided, however, that each Co-Tenant shall Transfer (such Transfer not requiring the consent of a Party) its rights and obligations under this Agreement and the LGIA, subject to the terms thereof, to a transferee of its respective Phase Controlled Assets (in which case such transferee shall be assigned and assume all of the Transferring Co-Tenant’s rights and obligations under both this Agreement and the LGIA, pursuant to an agreement reasonably satisfactory to the other Co-Tenants). Co-Tenant’s Right to Encumber. Notwithstanding anything in Section 4. 1 to the contrary, each Co-Tenant may, at any time and from time to time during the term of this Agreement, encumber, mortgage or hypothecate to any Financing Party by deed of trust or mortgage or other security instrument, (the “Mortgage”) all or part of such Co-Tenant’s interest under this Agreement and the other documents entered into in connection with this Agreement, including, without limitation, the LGIA, without the consent of the other Co-Tenants. Certain Rights of Financing Party. Should a Co-Tenant incur any encumbrance in accordance with Section 4. 2 of this Agreement, and should the Parties receive notice thereof pursuant to Section 5. 1 hereof, the Parties hereby expressly stipulate and agree as follows:(a) Modification of Agreement. They will not materially modify this Agreement or voluntarily cancel this Agreement without the written consent of the Financing Party, which consent may not be unreasonably withheld or delayed. (b) Performance by Financing Party. The Financing Party shall have the right to do any act or thing required of the encumbering Co-Tenant under this Agreement, and any such act or thing performed by the Financing Party shall be as effective to prevent an applicable default under this Agreement and/or a forfeiture of any of such Co-Tenant’s applicable rights under this Agreement as if done by the Co-Tenant itself. (c) Notice to Financing Party. If Manager issues or receives any notices regarding potential or actual defaults as described in Section 2. 18 herein, the Manager, on behalf of the Co-Tenants, shall promptly deliver a copy of such notice to all Financing Parties of which it has received notice. (d) Consents to Assignment. Each Co-Tenant and the Manager hereby agrees that it shall, no later than five (5) business days after a request by a Co-Tenant (the “Requesting Co-Tenant”) (or its Financing Party), execute such consents or estoppel certificates as are reasonably requested by the Requesting Co-Tenant or its Financing Party. FERC Approval. Notwithstanding anything in Section 4. 1 or 4. 2 to the contrary, no Transfer of a Co-Tenant’s interests in this Agreement shall be effective unless and until the Co-Tenant or the Manager has obtained any necessary prior approvals from the FERC to effectuate any changes to this Agreement to reflect such Transfer and the change in the parties to this Agreement.
